📌 Overview

Organizations today face unexpected crises such as supply chain disruptions, cyberattacks, pandemics, climate events, and sudden cost spikes. These events rarely occur in isolation—one disruption often triggers multiple downstream failures across operations.

Most mid-sized organizations lack access to advanced simulation tools and rely on static Excel-based what-if analysis, which fails to model real-world dependencies and cascading effects.

This project aims to solve that gap by building a No-Code AI Crisis Simulation Platform that allows non-technical operations teams to create, simulate, and mitigate crisis scenarios visually and interactively.

🎯 Problem Statement

Current crisis simulation tools:

Require data scientists or complex modeling

Are expensive and inaccessible

Do not support fast, interactive decision-making

As a result, operations leaders cannot accurately predict ripple effects or test mitigation strategies during high-pressure situations.

💡 Solution

This platform provides:

A drag-and-drop no-code interface to build crisis scenarios

A simulation engine that models cascading impacts across operations

Risk scores, impact analysis, and recovery forecasts

Mitigation testing to compare strategies before execution

All without writing a single line of code.

🚀 Features

Drag-and-drop crisis scenario builder

Multi-crisis simulation support

Cascading impact analysis

Mitigation strategy testing

Quantified risk scoring

Visual dashboards and reports

Fast and explainable simulations

🏗️ System Architecture
Frontend

Visual scenario editor

Interactive dashboards

Real-time simulation updates

Backend

Scenario processing APIs

Simulation and dependency engine

Risk scoring and recommendation logic

Data Layer

Scenario storage

Simulation results

Historical analysis

🛠️ Technology Stack
Frontend

React.js / Next.js

Tailwind CSS

React Flow (for drag-and-drop scenarios)

Backend

Python

FastAPI / Flask

REST APIs

AI & Simulation

Rule-based cascading logic

Weighted risk scoring algorithms

Machine learning models (optional extension)

Database

PostgreSQL / MySQL

MongoDB (optional)

Visualization

Chart.js / Recharts / D3.js

⚙️ How It Works

User selects or creates crisis events

Events are connected to operational units

System simulates cascading effects

User applies mitigation strategies

Platform recalculates impacts and risks

Results are shown via dashboards and reports

📂 Project Structure
